Conclusions loading generation dataset¶

I have discharged and loaded all the files containing generation by technology These files are different from the file structure followed fot prices and demand Discharged files includes monthly files with detailed information for each hour of the day There are four versions of the published files. - L0 (original data) contains the original data publised on the 7 days after the day operation in the market - L1 (initial reliquidation) includes a more accurate information 49 days after the daily operation in the market (this information sustitutes the L0 information) - L2 (intermediate reliquidation) includes a more accurate information 105 days after the daily operation in the market (this information sustitutes the L0 and L1 information) - L3 (final reliquidation) includes a more accurate information 210 days after the daily operation in the market (this information sustitutes the L0, L1 and L2 information) - L4 (controversial reliquidation) only appears on the cases revised. I have discharged the latest available version of the file up to date and L4' version if available. And copied the files on their corresponding folder (Opath_LXX_Gen)

Loading dataset generation process (Similar to the process to load prices and demands)¶

The process followed to load data is the following: - I have created a function that opens one of the csv file and read its contend. - The funcion creates a dataframe including the columns obtained from the dataframe (a little bit modified) - Also creates one column as datestime, very useful to locate specific data - Once the dataframe is created and filled in with data from the csv, it is appended as an element to a list of dataframes (LoDf) and I repeat the process for all the files included on the specific folder. - Once all the files of the folder have been treated, I use the pandas dataframe.concat method to all dataframes of the list of dataframes created and obtain a dataframe including all data of the specific folder and I append this final dataframe as an element to a list. -I repeat the process for each of the folders and obtains a list with a final dataframe per folder. To avoid reapeating this process everytime, I saved each element of the list (dataframes) on a csv file on the specified destination folder And also created a dataframe saved to a csv including all the treated files (columns = folder name and elements= file names) (I will refer later to this dataframe as preloaded list) Method followed to speed up data adquisition process: - Prior to the process explained above, I created a list including all the name of the files in each folder (actual list) - This list is compared with a previously generated list of files per folder (preloaded list) - If there is any new file present in the actual list that is not included on the preloaded list, this file is treated. - I load saved dataframe per folder (if exist) and uses it as first element of the dataframes list (LoDf), the new files are appended as new elements to this list - Later I concat all the elements of the Lodf (dataframes) and append it to a complete dataframe per folder that, as before explained is saved to a csv file - Dataframe containing file names per folder is updated to include new treated files. To create a final dataframe incluiding all the generation info, I have used the pandas dataframe merge method. To merge L0 to L3 dataframes, I have used the parameter how='outer' since there is no intersection between L0 to L3 datasets. As for merged dataframe (L0 to L3) and L4 dataframe I have used as parameter how='left' but only on on=['Fecha','Día','Mes','Año','Hora'] columns, since I do not want to include more elements to the rows, since total number of rows has to be equal to (nº of days+1) times 24 hours = 16059 values (from 1-1-18 to 31-10-19) this process created several additional columns, I created the original ones (without suffix) as a fillna method with the L4 dataframe I included a little test (modifying manually one input I confirmed that merged dataframe was updated). (I have realized after having prepared the model to update L0,L1,L2 and L3 data, that information published by Cenace as L4 has not changed information published on files L0 to L3, but it doesn't mean they could not change the information, and in that case, the model will reflect those changes in data) To finish the proces, I drop the suffixed columns.

In this process: First I have discarted all the rows that do not have values on the prices and demands but have values on the commodities' dataframe (future values). Second, I have discarted all the rows that do not have values on the generation production by technology. Preparation of model_dataset to train the model - Feature selection¶

Looking into data I wold like to highlight the main factors observed on available data: - Regions: 108 regions - Prices: Price is the sum of its components. Energy component is equal for each hour to all the regions of the SIN (Sistema Interconectado Nacional- 101 regions) - Demands:Total demand is the sum of its components - Commodities: Available data only provides daily commodities (It doesn't make sense otherwise, since fuels are bought with purchase contracts with formula prices that avoid volatibility of costs. - Generation by technology: Data available provides houly production by technology for the agregate of the 108 regions SEN (Sistema Eléctrico Nacional) So I would have to choose features consequently in order to obtain predictions of: Hourly Energy Component Prices for the Sistema Interconectado Nacional Process and explanations could be found on the following points define the target feature. In this case, the feature ['Componente de energia ($/MWh)'] is common for all the - 1st I will map the regions to a numerical code

Regions selection¶

In [28]:
df.sort_values(by=['Fecha_completa'], ascending=True)[['Nodo o Region','Componente de energia ($/MWh)']]
#It seems that this value is similar for all the Sistema Interconectado Nacional regions, and different for Baja California and Baja California Sur
dfdivision=caf.group_by_division(df)
print(dfdivision)
# I mapped the regions to the divisions they are part of.
# Doing so, we can observe that this component is the same each hour for for all the regions except for those of Baja California and Baja California Sur
# Therefore I will drop this regions in order to have less variability on predictions
for i in ['ENSENADA','MEXICALI','SANLUIS','TIJUANA','CONSTITUCION','LA PAZ','LOS CABOS']:
    index_to_drop=df[df['Nodo o Region']==i].index
    df.drop(index_to_drop, inplace=True)   
print(len(set(df['Nodo o Region'])))

Price features selection¶

In [29]:
df['Precioprima']=df['Componente de energia ($/MWh)']+df['Componente de perdidas ($/MWh)']+df['Componente de congestion ($/MWh)']
print(df[(df['Precio']-df['Precioprima'])>0.1])

''' This result confirms that these features are lineally correlated. I will therefore discard ['Precio','Componente de perdidas ($/MWh)' and 'Componente de congestion ($/MWh)']'''

df.drop(['Precioprima','Precio','Componente de perdidas ($/MWh)','Componente de congestion ($/MWh)'], axis=1, inplace=True)

Checking on aggregated hourly productions and aggregated houly Total demands¶

In [33]:
df['Total_prod']=df['Eolica']+df['Fotovoltaica']+df['Biomasa']+df['Carboelectrica']+df['Ciclo Combinado']+df['Combustion Interna']+df['Geotermoelectrica']+df['Hidroelectrica']+df['Nucleoelectrica']+df['Termica Convencional']+df['Turbo Gas']
Hourlydemand=pd.DataFrame(df.groupby(['Fecha','Hora'])['Demanda total (MWh)'].sum())
df=pd.merge(left= df,right=Hourlydemand, how='left', on=['Fecha','Hora'])
df.rename(columns={'Demanda total (MWh)_y':'Aggregated total demand (MWh)'},inplace=True)
df['Demand/prod']=(df['Aggregated total demand (MWh)']/df['Total_prod'])-1
# I will keep productions and the relation of that with Demanda Total, dropping the last one
df.drop(['Demanda total (MWh)_x','Aggregated total demand (MWh)'], axis=1,inplace=True)
